{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539308"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16585"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16585"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.37,0.44,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66041"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9276"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51498"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"267"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"3579"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"7102"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21984"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22078"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66041"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening headaches and occasional episodes of blurred vision. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals bilateral papilloedema but is otherwise unremarkable. A magnetic resonance imaging scan of the brain is arranged.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common type of primary brain tumour in adults?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acoustic neuroma","Glioblastoma","Meningioma","Oligodendroglioma","Pituitary adenoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPrimary brain tumours are classified based on their cell of origin, with \u003Cstrong\u003Emeningiomas\u003C/strong\u003E being the most common type in adults, accounting for approximately 37% of all primary brain tumours. They arise from the arachnoid cap cells of the meninges and are typically slow-growing and benign, though their clinical impact can be significant depending on location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlioblastoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common malignant primary brain tumour in adults but is less common overall than meningioma. It is an aggressive tumour with a poor prognosis, typically presenting in older adults with rapidly progressive neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary adenomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign tumours arising from the anterior pituitary gland. While relatively common, they account for about 15% of primary brain tumours, making them less frequent than meningiomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcoustic neuromas\u003C/strong\u003E (vestibular schwannomas) arise from the eighth cranial nerve and typically present with unilateral hearing loss and tinnitus. They represent only about 8% of primary brain tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOligodendrogliomas\u003C/strong\u003E are relatively rare tumours arising from oligodendrocytes, accounting for less than 5% of primary brain tumours. They typically present in middle-aged adults and have a better prognosis than other gliomas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe epidemiology of brain tumours shows significant age and gender variations. Meningiomas are more common in women, with a female-to-male ratio of about 2:1, and their incidence increases with age. The peak age of diagnosis is between 50 and 70 years.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meningiomas account for approximately one-third of all primary brain tumours in adults.","Most meningiomas are benign and slow-growing, but their clinical impact depends on location.","The incidence of meningiomas increases with age and is higher in women than men."],"references":["Ogasawara C, Philbrick BD, Adamson DC. Meningioma: A Review of Epidemiology, Pathology, Diagnosis, Treatment, and Future Directions. Biomedicines. 2021 Mar 21;9(3):319. doi: 10.3390/biomedicines9030319. PMID: 33801089; PMCID: PMC8004084.","Maggio I, Franceschi E, Tosoni A, Nunno VD, Gatto L, Lodi R, Brandes AA. Meningioma: not always a benign tumor. A review of advances in the treatment of meningiomas. CNS Oncol. 2021 Jun 1;10(2):CNS72. doi: 10.2217/cns-2021-0003. Epub 2021 May 21. PMID: 34015955; PMCID: PMC8162186.","Wiemels J, Wrensch M, Claus EB. Epidemiology and etiology of meningioma. J Neurooncol. 2010 Sep;99(3):307-14. doi: 10.1007/s11060-010-0386-3. Epub 2010 Sep 7. PMID: 20821343; PMCID: PMC2945461."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16585"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51498"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T08:51:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T08:51:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9276"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions",